actions.args: {"handle": "zero-knowledge", "community_addon": {"id": "8m9guu", "enabled": true, "addon_id": "wiki", "parameters": "{\\\\\\\"title\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Projects\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"subtitle\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"content\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"If you have a ZK project building on NEAR and would like it featured here or have an update for a featured project, please fill out this [Google form](https://forms.gle/whyTeNXBWUYJAnpn7).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Electron Labs\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nElectron is building the next generation of ZK-Light clients that enable ZK-proving of consensus protocols. Electron is launching ZK-Proof aggregation that will enable multiple proofs from different chains to be aggregated together into a single proof.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### How to contribute \\\\\\\\nThe project is open source. Anyone who wishes to collaborate can open a PR via [GitHub](https://github.com/Electron-Labs).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Links \\\\\\\\n- [Website](https://electronlabs.org/)\\\\\\\\n- [GitHub](https://github.com/Electron-Labs)\\\\\\\\n- [Twitter](https://twitter.com/labs_electron)\\\\\\\\n- [LinkedIn](https://www.linkedin.com/company/electron-labs/)\\\\\\\\n- [Youtube](https://www.youtube.com/@electronlabs)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Zpoken\\\\\\\\nZpoken is a web3 development organization focusing on cryptography research and decentralized tech. Zpoken is building a NEAR ZK Light Client. \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### How to contribute\\\\\\\\nThe project is open source. Anyone who wishes to collaborate can open a PR via [GitHub](https://github.com/ZpokenWeb3).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Links\\\\\\\\n- [Website](https://zpoken.io/)\\\\\\\\n- [GitHub](https://github.com/ZpokenWeb3)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Opact\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nOpact is a decentralized private transactions protocol designed for well-intended users. It breaks the link between the sender and the receiver of a transaction utilizing zero-knowledge proofs. To be able to use it, you have to be accepted into an allowlist connected to KYT providers, which block wallets involved in malicious activities, such as hacking.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### How to contribute \\\\\\\\nThe project is open source. Anyone who wishes to collaborate can open a PR via [Github](https://github.com/opact-protocol) directly or get in contact with Hack-a-Chain\\\\u{2019}s team on [Telegram](t.me/hackachain).\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Links\\\\\\\\n- [Website](https://www.opact.io/)\\\\\\\\n- [Application](https://tickets.opact.io/)\\\\\\\\n- [Docs](https://docs.tickets.opact.io/)\\\\\\\\n- [Github](https://github.com/opact-protocol)\\\\\\\\n- NEAR ZK Tools \\\\\\\\n    - [Groth16 verifier](https://crates.io/crates/near_groth16_verifier)\\\\\\\\n    - [Plonk verifier](https://github.com/opact-protocol/tickets/tree/main/packages/contract-libraries/plonk_verifier)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Reclaim Protocol\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nReclaim Protocol creates digital signatures, known as zero knowledge proofs, of users\\\\\\' identity and reputation on any website. You could ask your user to login into Uber and prove that they\\\\\\'ve taken more than 50 rides this year. All of this happens without compromising security and without needing any change on the bank\\\\\\'s or Uber\\\\\\'s side.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### How to contribute \\\\\\\\nThe project is not open source.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Links \\\\\\\\n- [Website](https://www.reclaimprotocol.org/)\\\\\\\\n- [Whitepaper](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1wmfdtIGPaN9uJBI1DHqN903tP9c_aTG2/view)\\\\\\\\n- [Developer portal](https://dev.reclaimprotocol.org/dashboard)\\\\\\\\n- [Demo](https://www.loom.com/share/15b503bcc5354595998f6579f8e81269)\\\\\\\\n- [Use cases built with Relcaim](https://blog.reclaimprotocol.org/posts/usecases/)\\\\\\\\n- [Reclaim at work](https://www.notion.so/Reclaim-at-Work-2eeda89565a74e9baf170504108b5319?pvs=21)\\\\\\\\n- [Integration docs](https://docs.reclaimprotocol.org/)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"textAlign\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"center\\\\\\\"}", "display_name": "Projects"}}

This community is all about hackathons. We\\\\u{2019}re here to build beyond the hype, crypto winter, pandemic, and war. We\\\\u{2019}re here to hack this world to perfection, or, at least, to being a better place through the power of BOS and blockchain technology.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## Our groups\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThe Hacks community consists of two main groups: \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Working group\\\\\\\\nThis formal group is a selected committee of subject matter experts who make official decisions on proposals and questions related to Hackathons and technical events on NEAR. They follow a strict process to review proposals, recommend funding to DAO, and hold grant takers accountable. They also engage with the broader community to understand their needs and encourage ideation. \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Members**\\\\\\\\n- Maria Yarotska @yarotska.near\\\\\\\\n- Vlad Frolov @frol.near\\\\\\\\n- Oleksii Tarazevich @drtarazevich.near\\\\\\\\n- Nneoma Kanu @nneoma.near\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n### Community Group\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\nThis informal self-organized group provides a space to discuss and implement ideas around developer focused events in and beyond the Near ecosystem. While this group does not make official decisions, it offers a great opportunity to meet with others to share ideas and submit proposals. This group is not controlled by anyone but the people who are organizing it. The group has a dedicated Telegram channel as well as regular Twitter spaces. \\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Communication Channels**\\\\\\\\n- [DevHub Hacks Community Group in Telegram](https://t.me/+Pdipk3olNgw3NWMy)\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n## How to get involved\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n- Join the community group\\\\\\'s dedicated [Telegram group](https://t.me/+Pdipk3olNgw3NWMy) to learn about the latest discussions and activities. Don\\\\u{2019}t forget to introduce yourself.\\\\\\\\n- Subscribe to DevHub\\\\u{2019}s [Twitter account](https://twitter.com/NEARDevHub) to make sure you don\\\\u{2019}t miss our monthly Spaces hangout.\\\\\\\\n- Participate in discussions, comment on existing ideas, or propose new ideas.\\\\\\\\n- Volunteer to speak about a topic or be a co-host for a Twitter Space.\\\\\\\"}", "display_name": "About"}, {"id": "s46evi", "enabled": true, "addon_id": "wiki", "parameters": "{}", "display_name": "Projects"}, {"id": "iqll86", "enabled": true, "addon_id": "wiki", "parameters": "{\\\\\\\"title\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"How to request support\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"content\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"We are always on the lookout for events that align with our mission and provide value to the NEAR ecosystem. If you are organizing such an event, we would love to hear from you! Below is a guide on how to submit a sponsorship proposal to us.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**Pre-Approval Criteria:**\\\\\\\\nYour proposal should address the following key areas that we use to evaluate event sponsorships:\\\\\\\\n1. Event Information: \\\\\\\\nProvide details about the event. This should include the scope, budget, target audience, goals, and expected outcomes of the event. (Refer to the template below)\\\\\\\\n2. Host Background: \\\\\\\\nTell us about your experience hosting similar events. Include past successes, what you\\\\\\'ve learned, and how you\\\\\\'ve grown your event-hosting skills.\\\\\\\\n3. Dev/Project Potential Stickiness: \\\\\\\\nExplain the relevance of the event to NEAR. Describe how the event will promote NEAR and foster growth in the NEAR ecosystem.\\\\\\\\n4. Post Execution Metrics: \\\\\\\\nAfter the event, we will be looking at these metrics to evaluate further possible collaboration:\\\\\\\\n5. Onboarded developers\\\\\\\\nProjects built on NEAR testnet/mainnet\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**How to Submit Your Proposal:**\\\\\\\\n- Go to the DevHub board.\\\\\\\\n- Click the \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Submit Idea/Solution\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" button.\\\\\\\\n- Create a new post using the template provided below and post it as an Idea.\\\\\\\\n- Allow us some time to assess and evaluate your proposal.\\\\\\\\n- Upon approval, receive an attestation of sponsorship.\\\\\\\\n- Congratulations! You\\\\\\'ve secured your sponsorship!\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**PROPOSAL TEMPLATE**\\\\\\\\nUse this template to structure your proposal. Make sure to provide detailed responses to each point.\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\n**[Your Organization] [Event Name] Proposal**\\\\\\\\n1. Event Introduction\\\\\\\\nProvide a brief explanation of your event, its overall goals, and its target audience.\\\\\\\\nExample: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"[Event Name] is a large festival designed for [target audience]. Our main goal is to promote [specific concepts or technology] among [target audience].\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n2. Organizer Introduction\\\\\\\\nDescribe who you are, any relevant credentials you have, and why you\\\\\\'re the right person/team to organize this event.\\\\\\\\nExample: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"[Your Organization] is the regional hub for everyone interested in [specific activity or field]. We have organized numerous programs and events that have helped [target audience] to [specific outcomes].\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n3. Event Impact\\\\\\\\nDescribe the expected outcome of the event, its significance in a broader context, and how it will further the goals of the field or community you\\\\\\'re working with.\\\\\\\\nExample: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"The [Event Name] will strengthen [Organization\\\\\\'s or Field\\\\\\'s Impact] in [region], and promote [specific concept or technology] to developers, builders, and creators in the region.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n4. Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)\\\\\\\\nProvide the expected metrics the event aims to achieve, such as the number of attendees, number of projects developed, and so on.\\\\\\\\nExample: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"We expect to attract over [number] developers, with [number] hackathon participants, and at least [number] projects. The event will feature [number] prizes across [number] categories.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n5. Evaluation Factors\\\\\\\\nProvide the criteria for judging the event\\\\\\'s success, especially if it\\\\\\'s a competition.\\\\\\\\nExample: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"Projects will be evaluated based on team composition, market potential, product innovation, business model, and growth strategy.\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n6. Funding Request\\\\\\\\nProvide a detailed breakdown of the requested funding, showing exactly how the funds will be allocated.\\\\\\\\nExample: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"We are requesting [$amount] for [specific allocation of funds].\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\\n7. Additional Information\\\\\\\\nInclude any further details, related links, or relevant attachments to support the proposal.\\\\\\\\nExample: \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"[Link to additional resources]\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\"}", "display_name": "Get Support"}, {"id": "bi1ycv", "enabled": true, "addon_id": "telegram", "parameters": "{\\\\\\\"handles\\\\\\\":[\\\\\\\"neardevhubhacks\\\\\\\"]}", "display_name": "Telegram"}], "handle": "hacks"}
